content:
Declaration Files (.d.ts)

Declaration files describe the shape of JavaScript code to TypeScript without providing implementation.

### What Are .d.ts Files?

Declaration files have a `.d.ts` extension and contain only type information — no runtime code.

```typescript
// types.d.ts
export interface User {
  id: number;
  name: string;
  email: string;
}

export function createUser(name: string, email: string): User;
```

### Ambient Declarations

Used to type external JavaScript libraries:

```typescript
// globals.d.ts
declare const API_VERSION: string;

declare function logToConsole(message: string): void;

declare namespace MyLib {
  function doSomething(): void;
}
```

### Declare Module

```typescript
// For libraries without TypeScript types
declare module "old-library" {
  export function doThing(): void;
  export const VERSION: string;
}

// Then you can import:
import { doThing } from "old-library";
```

### Triple-Slash Directives

```typescript
/// <reference types="node" />
/// <reference path="./types.d.ts" />
```

### Generating Declaration Files

In `tsconfig.json`:

```json
{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "declaration": true,
    "declarationDir": "./types"
  }
}
```

### Module Augmentation

Add types to existing modules:

```typescript
// augmentations.d.ts
import "some-library";

declare module "some-library" {
  interface SomeInterface {
    newProperty: number;
  }
}
```

> **Key Point:** Declaration files enable TypeScript to understand untyped JavaScript code.

codeExample:
// jquery.d.ts - Ambient declaration for a library
declare module "jquery" {
  function $(selector: string): JQuery;

  interface JQuery {
    addClass(className: string): JQuery;
    removeClass(className: string): JQuery;
    text(content?: string): string;
  }

  export default $;
}

// Global augmentation
declare global {
  interface Window {
    myApp: {
      version: string;
    };
  }
}

// Usage
window.myApp = { version: "1.0.0" };
